 \section{Introduction}
-ARC-AGI-3~\cite{chollet2019measure, arcagi3} consists of interactive grid games whose
-rules are withheld. An agent observes a $64\times64$ array of colour values, chooses
-among a small set of opaque actions, and receives sparse feedback when a level is
-completed. It must infer useful perceptual categories, mechanics, objectives, and plans
-from interaction. Successive levels create a second problem beyond task completion:
-determining whether competence transfers or whether each level is solved anew.
-
-This distinction is obscured by aggregate scores. A solver that composes a previously
-learned routine and one that stores a newly recovered action sequence may reach the same
-level, but they provide different evidence about generalization. The distinction is
-especially relevant for coding agents, whose iterative write--execute--revise loops are
-effective on ARC-style tasks~\cite{arcprize2025}, and for ARC-AGI-3 approaches based on
-exploration graphs or executable world models~\cite{arcagi3graph,arcagi3worldmodels}.
-Their executable artifacts can make structural growth observable, provided solve
-boundaries, retained dependencies, and source changes are kept distinct.
-
-We use \emph{self-improving agent} in a restricted operational sense: the composite
-system revises retained task-solving code across levels, and replay-validated artifacts
-become the starting point for subsequent revisions. The harness and learning protocol
-remain fixed. Thus the term denotes cumulative, verifier-gated program improvement, not
-unrestricted self-modification or proof-theoretic optimality.
-
-We call this architecture the \emph{G\"odel--Kolmogorov Machine}. ``G\"odel'' marks
-the inheritance of self-revision under a verification gate, although our gate is
-empirical replay rather than G\"odel-machine proof search. ``Kolmogorov'' marks the
-description-length selection pressure and structure-function analysis. The compound
-name therefore states the architecture's two commitments rather than asserting
-proof-theoretic optimality or machine-independent complexity measurement.
-
-We study the following question: \emph{Can a verifier-gated coding agent grow new solver
-structure when mechanics change, reuse that structure when it applies again, and reduce
-the marginal description cost of later competence?} The G\"odel--Kolmogorov Machine
-maintains a shared library, level bindings, and a chain of replay-validated promotions.
-The game runtime validates behavioral progress; the source ledger measures when
-executable structure enters the chain. A diagnostic free-energy quantity combines
-replay progress with cumulative historical charge, while a separate
-retained-description functional organizes the structure-function analysis below.
-
-The preserved histories answer this question positively on the observed games. New
-mechanics enter as charged source extensions; recurring mechanics are implemented by
-thin players calling unchanged legs and produce sharp marginal-cost troughs; and
-debriefs can reorganize a verified behavior into a reusable factorization without
-changing its replay. The scalar ledger is not a semantic oracle: same-size replacement
-can be free, and a small player can call either a reusable routine or an opaque retained
-plan. Its role is evidential. Adjacent source, named calls, and fresh replay make each
-structural attribution testable. Kolmogorov structure functions describe executable
-size at verified fit; policy colimits describe compatible behavior; and cofibration
-filtrations retain the order of acquisition.
-
-The paper makes four contributions. First, it introduces the
-G\"odel--Kolmogorov Machine as a self-improving solver-growth approach that alternates
-proposal, composition from an incumbent library, replay-gated promotion, and post-level
-refactoring. Second, it formalizes compatible partial-policy colimits, trace
-cofibrations, and replay equivalence, explaining why an endpoint colimit alone loses
-acquisition history. Third, it demonstrates the approach's intended structural
-properties in preserved histories: charged novelty acquisition, named-routine reuse,
-and large drops in marginal complexity when prior structure suffices. Fourth, it
-reports eight promoted endpoints on a closed Competition-Mode scorecard, with complete
-chronological traces for two games and executable artifacts that expose the claims to
-countertest. This is evidence for a resource-bounded solver-growth approach, not merely
-an accounting proposal and not a compute-matched comparison with other systems.
-Having established the full name and its scope, we abbreviate the
-G\"odel--Kolmogorov Machine as \emph{GKM} below.
-
